# Interface contracts

Subclasses must respect their base class method signatures exactly. Do not add
extra parameters to overridden methods.

```ruby
# BAD: breaks the interface
class CmakeIntegration < Integration
  def install_all(dependencies, root:)  # extra param
  end
end

# GOOD: subclass-specific context via constructor
class CmakeIntegration < Integration
  def initialize(repository:, cache:, project_root:)
    super(repository:, cache:)
    @project_root = Pathname(project_root)
  end

  def install_all(dependencies)
    # uses @project_root
  end
end
```

Use constructor DI **only** for values that are:
- Fixed for the lifetime of the object (not changing per call)
- Subclass-specific context the base interface doesn't define
- Not the method's direct input

Regular method parameters are correct when the value changes per call or is
the method's primary input (e.g. `lock(deps)` — different deps each time).
